article.description: Playing without suspended star Pops Mensah-Bonsu,  George Washington beat Kennesaw State 87-42 on Wednesday night behind Mike Hall's 22 points and 10  rebounds.
article.headline: GW dusts DI newcomer Kennesaw
article.linkText: George Washington has little trouble with Kennesaw
article.story: WASHINGTON (AP) -- During pregame warmups, Pops Mensah-Bonsu stood on the sideline, his left arm cradling a basketball and his right hand aloft for high-fives from his George Washington teammates. That was as close to the action as the suspended star would get during the Colonials' (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) season opener Wednesday night, and it mattered little in a game pitting a nationally ranked team against a Division I newcomer. George Washington concentrated on playing tough defense against its outmatched foe, and Mike Hall had a career-high 22 points and 10 rebounds in the Colonials' 87-42 victory over Kennesaw State. "We're very balanced. We're not a basketball team that counts on one guy," GW coach Karl Hobbs said. "Obviously we miss him tremendously. We're not as good a team without him. He's a huge, huge loss for us, and we'll have to find a way to play two more games without him." Mensah-Bonsu -- a senior forward who received votes for the AP's preseason All-America team -- is sitting out three games for rules violations related to his early declaration and withdrawal from the NBA draft. "There's some things that involve when guys put their name in for the draft -- I just think there needs to be more clarity with some of the rules, and I'll just leave it at that," Hobbs said. Hall shot 7-for-7 in the first half and finished 10-for-12. The senior -- who also declared for, then pulled out of, the June draft -- surpassed his previous scoring best of 19 with a dunk 3½ minutes into the second half that made it 51-25. "We just have an open offense with a lot of guys that are interchangeable," Hall said. Carl Elliott added 14 points, and Maureece Rice had 11 of his 13 in the second half for the Colonials, who were the last team in the AP preseason poll to play a regular-season game. They won their 17th straight home opener, before a crowd of 2,217. Ronnell Wooten scored 10 for Kennesaw State (1-3), which won the 2003-04 Division II championship and moved up this year to the Atlantic Sun Conference. Already shorter than GW at every position, Kennesaw State found itself in more trouble when center Dusty Moore, at 6-foot-8 the Owls' tallest starter, picked up three fouls in the first 3 minutes and sat the rest of the half. The highlight for the Owls had to be the 6-4 Wooten's dunk over 6-11 Alex Kireev to pull the visitors to 25-17 about 11½ minutes into the game. But Kennesaw State made only one more basket in the half and trailed 39-19 at the break. Hobbs was particularly pleased with his team's defense. GW allowed Division II Augusta State to score 96 points in a preseason game Nov. 12. "We spent all those days -- it's the most I think we've ever spent -- on defense," the coach said. Using occasional full-court pressure and trapping D, George Washington harassed the Owls into 26 turnovers and limited them to 32-percent shooting. GW held a 43-28 rebounding edge. Kennesaw State's Golden Ingle, who entered averaging a team-high 18.7 points, was held to seven on 3-of-12 shooting. Last season, the Colonials won 22 games and were the Atlantic-10 champions, earning an NCAA Tournament berth. With four returning starters led by Mensah-Bonsu and Hall, GW was in the AP preseason men's basketball poll for the third time. "The goal for this team is to win the Atlantic-10 championship and to be one of those 64 teams in the NCAA Tournament, and this was a step toward that. Each game, we have to get better," Hobbs said. "The last exhibition game that we played, we did not play at a high level. We did not play like a team that's out to accomplish something special." Mensah-Bonsu also will miss games against Norfolk State and St. Francis, Pa., then can make his season debut Dec. 2 against Boston University.
